<h1> U-statistics</h1>




<h3>Computing variance of 1-sample U-statistics</h3>

We have already seen that if U is a one sample U-statistic with kernel ,
h then 

<blockquote>
E(U) = E(h)
</blockquote>

Now we shall compute Var(U).

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise USTAT2.1:</font></b> 
   
   Let h be a kernel and let g be another defined as
   
   <blockquote>
   g(.) = h(.) - c,
   </blockquote>
   
   where c is some constant. If U<sub>h</sub> and U<sub>g</sub> are the
   U-statistics with kernels h and g, respectively, then show that
   
   <blockquote>
   U<sub>g</sub> = U<sub>h</sub>-c.
   </blockquote>
   
   Hence argue that for computing Var(U<sub>h</sub>) we can assume wlg that E(h)=0.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
We shall also assume wlg that h: <b>R</b><sup>m</sup>
                                                     <img src=
                                                     "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
                                                     align=middle>
                                                     
                                                     <b>R</b> is
symmetric. Define for 1
                       <img src=
                       "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                       align=top>
                       
                        k 
                          <img src=
                          "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                          align=top>
                          
                           m,

<blockquote>
h<sub>k</sub>(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>k</sub>) = 
E(h(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>m</sub>)| X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>k</sub>)

</blockquote>

<p>
We shall use the following notation:

<blockquote>
If K 
     <img src="resources/statinf2/subset.png"
     align=top>
      {1,...,n} then <u>X</u><sub>K</sub> will
 denote the
collection of X<sub>i</sub>'s with i in K.
</blockquote>


<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise USTAT2.2:</font></b> 
   
   Show, using symmetry of h, that h<sub>k</sub> is also symmetric in its k
   arguments.
   Also show that if K 
                       <img src="resources/statinf2/subset.png"
                       align=top>
                        I 
                          <img src="resources/statinf2/subset.png"
                          align=top>
                           {1,...,n} with
   |I| = m and |K| = k then  
   
   <blockquote>
   E(h(<u>X</u><sub>I</sub>|<u>X</u><sub>K</sub>)) =
    h<sub>K</sub>(<u>X</u><sub>K</sub>).
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise USTAT2.3:</font></b> 
   
   Show that E(h<sub>k</sub>(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>k</sub>) = 0.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

Define

<blockquote>
S<sub>k</sub> = Var(h<sub>k</sub>) =
E(h<sub>k</sub><sup>2</sup>)
</blockquote>

We shall compute Var(U) in terms of the S<sub>k</sub>'s.

<p>
Let K = I 
          <img src="resources/statinf2/inter.png">
           J and |K| = k  &gt; 0.
Then 

<blockquote>


<table border=0>


<tr>
<td align=right>
cov(h(X<sub>I</sub>), h(X<sub>J</sub>)
</td>
<td>
=
</td>
<td align=left>

 E(h(X<sub>I</sub>), h(X<sub>J</sub>))
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td align=right>

</td>
<td>
=
</td>
<td align=left>
E[E(h(X<sub>I</sub>).h(X<sub>J</sub>|X<sub>K</sub>)]
</td>
</tr>


</table>


</blockquote>
 
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise USTAT2.4:</font></b> 
   
   Show that
   
   <blockquote>
   E[ h(X<sub>I</sub>).h(X<sub>J</sub>)|X<sub>K</sub> ] = 
   h<sub>k</sub><sup>2</sup>(X<sub>K</sub>).
   </blockquote>
   
   Hence show that
   
   <blockquote>
   cov(h(X<sub>I</sub>), h(X<sub>J</sub>)) = S<sub>k</sub>.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise USTAT2.5:</font></b> 
   
   Show that the number of subsets I,J of {1,...,n} of size
   m with |I 
             <img src="resources/statinf2/inter.png">
              J| = k, is 
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <sup>n</sup>C<sub>m</sub> 
                             <sup>m</sup>C<sub>k</sub> 
                                                       <sup>n-m</sup>C<sub>m-k</sub>.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise USTAT2.6:</font></b> 
   
   Conclude that 
   
   <blockquote>
   Var(U) = 
            <img src=
            "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
            align=middle>
            
            
            <sup>n</sup>C<sub>m</sub> 
                                      <sup>m</sup>C<sub>k</sub> 
                                                                <sup>n-m</sup>C<sub>m-k</sub>
   S<sub>k</sub>/ (
                   <sup>n</sup>C<sub>m</sub>)<sup>2</sup>.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise USTAT2.7:</font></b> 
   
   Use the above exercise to compute Var(sample variance).
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   




